segments.text: You want to give me my, no, you want to give me my choice?
What?
You want to give me my choice?
Coffee, tea, oil?
Yeah.
Okay.
Two?
Please.
Please.
I've got to stay awake.
What's wrong with you this afternoon?
I had wine for lunch.
I've always maintained the time to bomb Washington is at 1230, given the lunches I always make with Congress.
I'm not kidding.
I was with the Smithsonian.
They really put a spread out.
OK, now, the next series of questions I have to ask concern relationships with other agencies.
And I'd like to tell you about the agency and then see what sort of input you think you had in direction or the direction the agency might happen to go.
The NSF, what was your attitude or relationship towards the National Science Foundation?
My attitude towards them has always been the same.
The more involvement the foundation has in oceanography, the better the program will be.

I see no competition between the foundation and anybody else, and was the key man who recommended the foundation take the Sea Grant program as opposed to Interior Commerce, who I didn't think, and still don't to this day, knows how to do anything outhouse.
And that's history.
It doesn't mean the people can't do it.
It's just, you know, just the tradition of an organization like the Department of Commerce or the Department of Interior is just an internal, in-house type of organization.
And I don't think you'd ever created an office of naval research type of environment, for example, had you ever started after the war in anybody but the Navy.
And you can say the Navy's a bureaucratic organization, but the way they did that, that certainly came out on top.
Well, I was going to ask about the ONR for a second.
I just want to follow that up.
People like Roger Revell, for example, give to the Navy total credit with the development both of the ONR and of oceanography.
I take it you would agree with that?
Initially, yes.
Okay.
So when time comes for the ONR to separate and, you know, not separate, that's too strong, but for the ONR to encourage the NSF to grow out of the ONR, after all, they did change in effect.
Well, I didn't know that they encouraged it.
I don't know who did that encouragement.
I came on the scene after NSF was established and when there was some competition between NSF and ONR, but there was no competition at the high level,

in oceanography and the highest level of the Navy very definitely encouraged both O and R to get better involved and deeper involved in oceanography and to get NSF deeper and more financially involved in oceanography.
And I think we succeeded in that if you look at the percentages of the pie within O and R devoted to oceanography and the percentage of the pie within NSF devoted to oceanography.
When you saw what seemed to be a competition when you came between ONR and NSF, what sort of competition or what did you think was the ingredient that caused the competition to occur?

Like any other bureaucracy, ONR was very proud of its history and very proud of its accomplishments and should be and should have been, but wasn't paying that much attention to what it ought to be doing in a changing world.
And therefore, I tried to get them out of nuclear physics and put the money in nuclear physics into oceanography, which I partially succeeded in, but didn't completely.
Because I don't think in today's world, or even in the mid-'60s world, that one could have doubled the budget just by putting new money in it.
When you make a decision like that, you have to figure out what you do in place of something.
And that's sometimes the hardest decision.
It's easy to say, if somebody gives me twice as much money, what I'm going to do.
It's a lot more difficult if somebody says, all right,
We feel this program is important.
You can go ahead and do it if you want to.
And that if you want to means you better kill something else in order to get it going.
That's natural.
That's human competition.
And that's good.
I felt that ONR was good.
I still feel it is good.

And the reason that I put the recommended and it was approved to put the Naval Research and Development Oceanographic Activity under the Chief of Naval Research was I think he's the best man to do the job.
And I could have put it directly under me instead of under him under me, or I could have put it under the Chief of Naval Materials Organization or the Director of Navy Labs.
I really believe that he's still the most competent to set up something that's that new in the world and that demanding and has that far to go.
And I hope that that flexibility will remain with ONR.
I don't know.
It's hard to foresee what will happen in the future.
Or what about NOAA?
Well, NOAA was also, in the year I was gone, it was also changed from, I guess, ESSA to NOAA.
In the early days in the 60s, I was trying to get, then it was what, the Coast and Geodetic Survey more involved.
I think it was Mr. Wakeman who was active in the legislation to get them a three-star admiral's billet as an assistant administrator.
I certainly appeared whenever I could with the then
the Coast and Geodetic Survey to support their budgets.
I still did before I was the NOAA deputy.
I do not appear now as NOAA deputy, nor do I appear as oceanographer because they're so big and, comparatively speaking, and have so many things to do, I can't just find the time.
But I sign letters that support their programs.
I feel it's very critical that NOAA be involved in the ocean.
I don't know that I would do it exactly the way that they're doing it.
But I don't know their problems as much as well as I know either the Foundation's problems or the Navy's problems.
I think I recognize NSF's problems in dealing with Congress and the Navy's problems.
But I don't always understand NOAA's problems, because NOAA is a conglomerate within the Department of Commerce.
I'm still a great supporter of NOAA trying to do the things that I think it ought to.
And I was willing and, in fact, recommended that they not create the Defense Mapping Agency, but they create a web mapping agency.
They either gave it to Noah or the Navy, and I would have voted giving it to Noah, finally.
I really felt that the only safeguard I'd have on that is to set the priorities so that I could override priorities if it were a real hard thing to do.
I had that arrangement with the Coast Guard.
I was instrumental in giving the Coast Guard the Navy's icebreakers back in the 60s.
And everybody said, oh, if you give it to them, they'll never do the job for you.
We'll never get this done, and we'll never get that done, and we'll never get the other done.
And the commandant of the Coast Guard
has always done what the Navy had to have done.
Not what the Navy wanted to get done, but when you had a Polaris problem or something really emergency, they were right there on top of it.
And I think it's come out very nicely.
And I don't see any reason why the same type of arrangement couldn't be with NOAA.
And we did transfer the data center to them, and we did transfer the instrument center.
I think that
They can do things a lot better.
But don't forget, they're also a new agency.
They're also growing rapidly.
The outside world likes to think they're not growing rapidly.
But if you look at their budget percentage-wise increase, it's been significant over the last four or five years.
I'd like to see them do a better job of mapping, a better job of environmental prediction.
And I'd like to see the Navy turn things over to that area or work with them.
I'm trying to work with them on the engineering side.
I have a dilemma here that it's not easy for me to give technology to a foreign country in an engineering sense.
So I've been trying to not interfere with what they're doing there.
On the other hand, I've committed to Dr. White to help him if he has a problem in engineering.
And I have helped him in the man in the sea program and do provide significant liaison for that.

I think there's a conflict between the agencies at the middle working level, but right at the present time and for the last two and a half years, I don't think I've seen a major conflict in the policy direction between NOAA and the Navy, with the possible exception of the Navy's view of technology exchange internationally versus NOAA's view.
And I don't know that I speak for Dr. White.
I know that the one echelon below, they'd like to give everything to everybody.
And I don't, that's not a,
agreed upon government position.
The rest is a lot easier now than I know it.
This is something that we sunk at midway that they dug back up and sunk us.

Now, in terms of relationships with Congress, do you see your primary role in Congress with that as, if I may use the word, a lobbyist for Navy oceanography or as an expert witness coming in for Naval oceanography or both?
I'd like to say I see it as a lobbyist, but I haven't been able to exercise that role.
And the reason I haven't is because of the controversy that's really surrounded moving something out of Washington.
I would like to do that because I think a lobbyist in the proper sense of the word is an important thing.
I think it's something the Navy hasn't done.
I think it's something the Navy should do.

As far as being a technical witness is concerned, that's probably the role I've played over the last 15 years or 10 years more than any other by merely trying to support the committees that are dealing in oceanography and not necessarily trying to lobby them for the Navy because they aren't the people who give the Navy the money.
And I have never appeared before the Navy's own committees but once.

I appeared as a commander in the mid-'60s in an attempt to get extra money for Navy ocean engineering, deep submergence, and believe it or not, was successful and was, I believe, one of the few times Mr. McNamara let the department accept an amount of money given to them over and above the president's budget by the Congress.
And it was $10 million, if I remember correctly.
It may have only been five, but it wasn't a lot of money.
It seemed like a lot of money to me at the time.
And it occurred right at the time we just recovered the hydrogen bomb.
I remember that because I remember the briefing I gave.
And I didn't give it as oceanography.
I gave it as special assistant to the secretary.
I prepare testimony for everybody, but I personally don't go before the Navy's own committees.
But I do go personally before the committees that are outside of the armed services, such as the Senate and the House committees that deal in oceanography.
and I do that in a technical sense, lobbying for oceanography in general and not lobbying for oceanography for the Navy.
Although if somebody asks me if the Navy can do a better job in this than somebody else, I'll tell them the truth, and some people don't like this.
If somebody asks me if the Navy can do a better job in charting than NOAA, I'll say, hell no, NOAA can do a better job.
If the Navy says to me, somebody says, can the Navy do a better job than the man in the sea, I'll say, hell yes, because it can.
It's got 4,000 people at sea, and I can give you all the reasons why it can do a better job.
Now, there may be bureaucratic reasons why the Navy ought not to do something, and that enters into it, and I think I'm pretty honest about that.
I think that you've got to put the Navy in it to get it started, but you don't want to keep the Navy in it.
And I think this is really what's happened in ocean science, too.
The Navy started it, and the Navy's not the major player now, but I think the Navy's still a major player, but not the major player.
And we have an abandoned ship, if you know what I mean.
On the other hand, we've let the Foundation take the lead, and yet we're working together with them.
I see no conflict in that because there's so much to be done.
And I don't think a naval officer such as myself is trying to perpetuate his own bureaucracy.

That doesn't mean I'm pure, but I think there's less incentive for me to do it than there is for somebody who makes a career out of a bureaucracy, although I've now been accused of it, as I'm sure you recognize.
Now, in terms of development of
of your department of oceanography here in effect in this ocean, what would you say were the most important accomplishments?
I mean, what time frame?
Oh, from between 60 and 75, the 15 years you've been here.
What are the things you're... Well, I don't take credit for all of them by a long shot.
I would say in the 60s, the major accomplishment was a significant increase in the academic program in oceanography and the training of oceanographers.
I think the 60s, what we did in the universities gave us the capability, assured the
this nation or this government ever really go into the sea in a big way, we have the qualified and capable people.
That's what we got academically out of the 60s.
We got new ships, and we sort of rebuilt up the fleet from World War II in oceanography.

We moved into deep submergence and ocean engineering in a big way for the first time, and I think got to a very significant position before we all of a sudden in the late 60s, like 68, 69, stopped doing much of anything.
I think in the, and we began to bring people together in the 60s.
The Interagency Committee on Oceanography and even the Marine Science Council and those things, I think, started to bring people together.
I think in the 70s what we accomplished, what we accomplished interagency-wise was the creation of a very fine

consolidation of the foundation and the Navy and NOAA Sea Grant in not under one management but under a understanding management and a cooperative effort in which I do work with them and we do know what they do and they do know what we do.
I think the other incentive or not incentive but I think the other some of the things that we've done that I think are very worthwhile are
the constant effort to declassify military information.
I think if that weren't run by the Secretary's office, you'd never get it done because the military mind always likes to say, keep out of my hair.
I think that the creation of the navigational satellite system has been absolutely magnificent from both a scientific and engineering viewpoint.
And that came out of the Polaris program.
I think the work that was done in the fleet ballistic missile system for hydrographic upgrading of the multi-beam echo sounder for the accuracy

and the building of the newer submersibles and the accomplishment of being able to start getting some instrumentation and hardware in deep submergence and undersea technology were accomplishments then.

The 70s accomplishments were only the one between the foundation and I suppose the rest of the accomplishments are those contained within the Navy in an attempt to try to crystallize the Navy's program and attempt to try to put it in a better perspective
I think I have lost in many of my objectives.
I think my objective of bringing the meteorologists and the oceanographer together was very selfish.
It was to broaden the base of manpower within the Navy, and that has been accomplished about a year ahead of schedule.
The ability to consolidate in a geographical location was a long, hard fight, and that's not over yet, but it's one third over.
I think the ability to get the management consolidation, which is not geographic, but to bring everybody working together is the next fight in the scene.
And the one that I've lost, which hurts me the most, is getting new capital investment objectives from the Navy Department to be able to help both the academic community and the Navy.
And I think, unfortunately, that's lost in my time.
If I'm lucky, I might be able to get something authorized, but it'll never be completed in my tour.
Now, when the consolidation process, of which you've run, do you think, roughly one-third, do you think...
I'm sorry.
Let me try it this way.
What will be the goals of the operation in Gulfport that will be different than your present goals?
To ensure that all of the Navy's effort in what we call ocean science, and you'd have to look at the instruction that talks about this because it's not academic science.
It goes a lot beyond that.
are fully integrated and coordinated, but not necessarily physically put in Gulfport, but are integrated with the effort of the academic community.
Not to drive the effort of the academic community, but have them working together towards a common understanding of the ultimate mathematical model of the world's ocean.

Now, you and I know we're not going to get from here to there, but that's the objective, and if you put your sight on that objective, even if you don't agree you can do such a thing, you can get an approximation to it,
We're all going to be better off, the fishermen, the merchant marine, the Navy, the submarine community, the weapons community, and the exploiting community such as the oil industry and the other.
In the prediction arena, that's to take what we learned from the science and get it out to the user.
The Navy's not doing too bad a job with that right now.
I'd like to be able to take that and get it out to all the users, not just the Navy users.
I'd like to do better within the Navy, but I'd like to also
get it out to the other users.
And that's hard to do because a lot of people suspect what you're doing when you do that.
But it's still worth a college try.
And by physically putting the director of that organization in the Navy in a geographical
office next door to the scientific world plus in-house development world, that may achieve what I hope it will achieve.
Then I take it that your hope is that the proximity of the people located in one spot will increase the efficiency and cooperation of your unit.
That's true, but it's got to be more than that.
You've got to direct them so that most of their work is going towards the objectives you want them to go for and not spending so much time
either fighting with each other or doing their own little administrative thing.
Now, the last series of interview questions I have on the fourth quarter interview are some general comments about naval career and naval civilian cooperation, if I may use that word.
First of all, in the 20th century Navy, if I may, do you see more of a move in the Navy into disciplines like oceanography, away from ship lines?
No, I don't.
I saw more of that in the 60s, and I've seen that sort of taper off.
I've seen the Navy attempt to go to the route of specialization in discipline fields, and then I've seen the Navy now in the last two years head back towards what you do at sea is what counts.

I'm very disappointed in that because the Navy's a damn big corporation, and it takes a lot of qualified people, and I'd like to see some of those qualified people military, even though I've been the one guy that pushed hard to civilianize the
The oceanographic programming have achieved most of that, but I still think that if you're going to run a Navy, the Naval officer better know enough about it to be able to run it.
But there's a danger there, and that is in a discipline like this, you have to stay so long you can jeopardize your own career militarily.
I think many people have.
I think that's probably why Don Walsh left the Navy.
I think he loved the Navy, but I think he felt he just spent too much time in oceanography and he couldn't compete with the...
I'd have to ask him, but that's my outside assessment.
Okay, so you see now what seemed to be the swing of the Navy in the 60s to integrate more and more managerial and scientific aspects now back to the ship-of-the-line approach.
That's what I see.
Whether that's accurate or not, that's certainly what I see.
All right.
Secondly, in terms of naval attitudes, would you agree that in terms of oceanography that you see more oceanographic work in, let's say, mapping, charting?
and deep sea work than you did in what seemed to be a generalized approach to oceanography in the 60s?
No.
That is oceanography becoming more specialized or less specialized?
Today I'd see it becoming less specialized than it was before.
I think before it tended to give the appearance of being specialized.
I think today there's been enough naval officers that have gone through graduate school and been exposed to it to recognize we know so little that they just can't.

narrow their focus, and I don't think they all know what they want, but I think there's quite a few naval officers around in the Admiral Circuit that either have sons in oceanography or have seen what it can do for them that give them at least a feel that it's important, although they can't necessarily articulate why it's important, nor would they put their own money in it.
But at least I think we've made that progress, and that's a carryover from the 60s when we educated people, I think.
Do you see any increase in hostility towards the military establishment?
By whom?
On the part of either Congress or civilians.
I don't.
A lot of people say that's going to happen.
But I've seen them come through what I consider a huge hostility during the Vietnam era.
And I've seen that hostility shift towards industrial corporations.
And I was talking to Mr. Mellon up in Pittsburgh about a year ago on that subject.
And I've also seen arguments that say that the Congress is very much against the military.
I think that's not exactly the case.
I think what you are seeing is the newer congressmen have not served in the military.
Therefore, they're not that familiar with it, number one.
Number two, their demands for national medical programs and social programs, that someday they're going to wake up.
You can't have always both things.
And I think this is going to affect the military budget
I would hope that it wouldn't affect the Navy as much as it would the Army or the Air Force, but you never can tell.
But I don't see an open animosity.
I see, I'm just as welcome, I'm more welcome right now than I was in the 69, 70 timeframe, but not as much as I was in the 63 to 66 timeframe.
If you had any advice to young career officers to begin here in the Navy, what would you say?
Would you say, go back to your alma mater, come into the Navy this way, be a regular naval man?
You mean instead of going to the Naval Academy or what?
I mean to go to the Naval Academy and come through or what?
Oh, I think the best way to advise a young man is to go to the Naval Academy and then take your graduate education somewhere outside of the Naval Academy.
That gives you the best of both worlds, in my opinion.
But you still think graduate education is necessary?
My own personal opinion is a naval officer is in a world that's so highly technical and so highly different from the rest of the world and its rapidity with its technology moves and a man who
is not have advanced education in today's world is just not the kind of guy I'd want to have if I had my ways about it.
And I think that it has another side benefit, and that is if you choose after 20 years to say to hell with the Navy, you've got some confidence to do some work on the outside.
I think it's an incentive program.
If I had my way, every enlisted man would get a college degree or a technical degree by the time he finished his 20 years, and every naval officer would have at least a master's degree.
and I wouldn't let them go on and make captain if they didn't, and I wouldn't let an enlisted man extend beyond his 20, and I think I owed it to him.
But then I'm not, that's my position, and that is not an agreed upon position, because a lot of people think I'm crazy about that.
But I really think in today's world that this corporation, which is 30 some billion dollars a year, needs a highly competent technical group of people working for it.
All right, now then, what, have you had any recommendations to young oceanographers?
What would you suggest?
Military or civilian?
Civilian oceanography.
Stay away from marine biology.
All right.
Stay away from marine biology.
And the reason I say that is because most of the people who have come into oceanography have come into it in the sense of the Jacques Cousteau world of the fishing and the diving.
And I think that oceanography is important and absolutely essential.
But it's not an easy subject.
It is not a basket weaving course.
It's a hard subject.
You've got to understand your math.
You've got to understand your physics.
You've got to understand what goes on in the ocean.
And I don't think you can do it by buying a scuba gear and just playing.
And I think that a lot of the young people tend to think that's the costos world of oceanography is the world they want to be a part of.
That's a fringe benefit to me.
But that's not why you ought to be doing it.
And I'm having that problem with the Naval Academy.
And I'm having that problem with postgraduate school and trying to harden up the math and the physics
in the curricula because we're getting a reputation these days of being a bunch of easygoing diving people.
And I think that's bad for both the community and I think that's bad for the Navy.
And I think it's true in both sides.
So when you look at a young student to bring him into your department here, if you civilianize your department, do you hunt for somebody with training in hard math and physics?
Well, I take biologists, too, but I think we're producing about three to one, three biologists for every man with a hard math background, and I think that it ought to be exactly the opposite ratio.
There ought to be three or four to one with a hard math ratio.
And even in the fishing and biology business, hard math has sure helped.
Because we're in the dark age as far as biology is concerned.
We're still using that plankton net that I think was invented in the 18th century.
And yet we've done much better in the other areas.
We're digitized and we're looking.
And I don't see why we can't.
That's a personal opinion, but I think a lot of the universities are beginning to see you've got to do the same sort of thing.
And I think we're all coming about to the same point.
Jack Cousteau is the greatest contribution
that I can think of to oceanography because I had he and his wife at the Secretary's mess, and that's how I sold the Secretary of the Navy into putting more money in oceanography.
But that's salesmanship.
That's lobbying.
We've got to produce now, and I think we've got to have a lot more sophisticated background than to be able to use the modern technology to be able to produce.
That's my own personal opinion.
Now, I have one other question, and that is, if someone came to you and said, Admiral Snyder, what's been your greatest contribution in terms of your career in the Navy and in oceanography?
In the Navy or in oceanography?
In the Navy first and in oceanography, one, two.
I don't know.
I don't think it's easy to ever say what you've contributed in the Navy.
I know what my happiest job was and my most rewarding job was, and that was, interestingly enough, in Vietnam.
where I had a ship and every Marine and every soldier was convinced that I saved his life.
And that's a pretty rewarding thing.
So that's hard to beat.
In the technical side, if I get it consolidated and if I get it under everybody working together, that will be a major accomplishment that nobody else has ever been able to do.
And I don't even know whether I can do it or not and get everybody working together.
I'm heading in that direction.
I hope to be able to say that
when I leave that that I have accomplished, at least set the stage for it going forward.
I guess that's about all I can say, because I think that in an organization this large, we tend to think one individual is able to make that significant a contribution.
But I think that the realities of life are that the only contribution I've made is persistence and obnoxiousness.
And unfortunately, on occasion, you can stand one guy in 1,000 who's that way.
